rker doing a similar job.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/understanding-your-pay/working-out-your-pay","slug":"working-out-your-pay","order":2,"title":"Working out your pay","body":"<p>Knowing how to work out your weekly pay is important because it&rsquo;s used to work out how much you should get for:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>redundancy pay and pay during time off for job-hunting if you&rsquo;re made redundant</li>\n  <li>pay during your notice period</li>\n  <li>holiday pay </li>\n  <li>guarantee pay for work (you get this if your employer can’t provide you with work, but your contract says they have to pay you anyway)</li>\n  <li>compensation awarded by Employment Tribunals</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>What you’re entitled to depends on <a href=\"/employment-status\" title=\"your work status\">your work status</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re paid weekly and your pay doesn&rsquo;t vary, you don&rsquo;t need to calculate your weekly pay. </p>\n\n<p>If your pay varies or you&rsquo;re not paid weekly, you have to use a 12-week period for working it out.</p>\n\n<h3>The 12-week period</h3>\n\n<p>This is where you work out your weekly pay by getting an average figure for a 12-week period. The period of time you use varies if you&rsquo;re calculating your pay for a specific reason.</p>\n\n<h3>Redundancy</h3>\n\n<p>To work out your pay during time off for job-hunting if you&rsquo;re being made redundant, use the 12-week period leading up to the day you got your redundancy notice.</p>\n\n<h3>Notice pay</h3>\n\n<p>If you want to know what your notice pay should be, use the 12-weeks leading up to the first day of the notice period.</p>\n\n<h3>Paid annual leave</h3>\n\n<p>Work this out using the 12 weeks leading up to your holiday.</p>\n\n<h3>Guarantee payments</h3>\n\n<p>Use the 12 weeks leading up to when your payment is due. If you no longer work for that employer, use the last 12 weeks of your employment with them.</p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;ve worked for your employer for less than 12 weeks, you should be allowed to calculate your average weekly pay using:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the number of hours you would have worked</li>\n  <li>the hours of other workers doing a similar job for your employer</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Working out your weekly figure</h3>\n\n<p>Add up the total amount of pay for the period and divide it by 12 to get the weekly figure. You do this even if you&rsquo;ve had to use a period of more than 12 weeks.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Bonuses can also be included - read the information on how to <a href=\"pay-calculations-if-you-work-shifts-or-get-bonuses\" title=\"work out your pay with bonuses\">work out your pay with bonuses</a> for help.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Overtime</h2>\n\n<p>If your contract says your employer has to pay you overtime, this can be included in your calculations.</p>\n\n<h2>Work done for a previous employer</h2>\n\n<p>You can include pay for work done for a previous employer if you&rsquo;re calculating your average weekly pay and you didn&rsquo;t have a gap in employment when you changed jobs.</p>\n\n<h2>If you don&rsquo;t have normal working hours</h2>\n\n<p>If you do shift or rota work, working out your weekly pay can be more complicated - read the advice on <a href=\"pay-calculations-if-you-work-shifts-or-get-bonuses\" title=\"calculations if you work shifts\">calculations if you work shifts</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>If you need help</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re having trouble calculating a week&rsquo;s pay, contact <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.acas.org.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1461\" title=\"Acas (Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service)\"><abbr title=\"Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service\">Acas</abbr> (Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service)</a> or <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/index/getadvice.htm#searchbox\" title=\"Citizens Advice\">Citizens Advice.</a></p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/understanding-your-pay/pay-calculations-if-you-work-shifts-or-get-bonuses","slug":"pay-calculations-if-you-work-shifts-or-get-bonuses","order":3,"title":"Pay calculations if you work shifts or get bonuses","body":"<p>If your pay or working hours vary from week to week, the calculations for working out your weekly pay are more complicated.</p>\n\n<h2>If your pay varies</h2>\n\n<p>Pay can vary depending on the amount of work you do, because of:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>bonuses</li>\n  <li>commission</li>\n  <li>&lsquo;piece-work&rsquo; - where you&rsquo;re paid by the amount of work you do, rather than by the hour</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If this is the case, to work out your weekly pay you need to work out your average hourly rate over a 12-week period. </p>\n\n<p>To do this, work out your total pay for the 12 weeks first. You can include overtime and bonuses. There are special calculations for bonuses.</p>\n\n<h2>Quarterly bonuses</h2>\n\n<p>If you get a quarterly bonus you can include a proportion of it in your calculations. Here&rsquo;s what to do:</p>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>Divide the amount by 13 (the number of weeks in a quarter of a year).</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Multiply this figure by 12 (the number of weeks your pay is averaged across).</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n\n<p>If you get a quarterly bonus of £260:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>divide £260 by 13 weeks = £20</li>\n  <li>multiply £20 by 12 weeks = £240</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can include a bonus of £240 as part of your 12-week total.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Annual bonuses</h2>\n\n<p>If you get an annual bonus here&rsquo;s what you need to do.</p>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>Divide the amount by 52 (the number of weeks in a year).</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Multiply this by 12.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n\n<p>If you get an annual bonus of £5,200:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>divide £5,200 by 52 weeks = £100 per week</li>\n  <li>multiply £100 by 12 weeks = £1,200</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can include a bonus of £1,200 as part of your 12-week total.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Once you&rsquo;ve worked out your total pay for the 12-week period, work out the average hourly rate by dividing the total by the number of hours you worked in the 12-week period. </p>\n\n<p>To work out your weekly wage, multiply your hourly rate by the average number of hours you worked each week in the 12-week period.</p>\n\n<h2>If you do shift or rota work</h2>\n\n<p>Your week’s pay will be the average number of hours you work at an average pay rate over a 12-week period.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Your pay is £6 per hour and you work 3, 9-hour shifts, then you have 3 days off. </p>\n\n<p>On weekends you&rsquo;re paid £9 per hour. At the start of the 12-week period, your first day at work is a Monday. Here&rsquo;s how you work out your pay.</p>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>Work out how many hours you did over the 12-week period (42 x 9-hour shifts = 378 hours).</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Divide this by 12 to work out your average weekly hours: 378 divided by 12 = 31.5 hours.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Calculate your pay for the weekday shifts. You’d have worked 30 weekday 9-hour shifts at £6 per hour. 30 shifts x 9 hours = 270 hours. Multiply this by £6 to get the total you were paid for your weekday shifts: £1,620.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Divide £1620 by 12 to get the weekly figure: £135.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Calculate your pay for weekends. You’d have worked 12 weekend 9-hour shifts at £9 per hour. 12 shifts x 9 hours = 108 hours. Multiply this by £9 to get the weekend total: £972</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Divide this by 12 to get the weekly figure: £81 per week.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Add the weekday and weekend figures together: £135 + £81 = £216. This is your weekly rate.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you need help</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re having trouble calculating a week&rsquo;s pay, contact <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.acas.org.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1461\" title=\"Acas (the Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service)\"><abbr title=\"Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service\">Acas</abbr> (Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service)</a> or <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/index/getadvice.htm#searchbox\" title=\"Citizens Advice\">Citizens Advice.</a></p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/understanding-your-pay/performancerelated-pay","slug":"performancerelated-pay","order":4,"title":"Performance-related pay","body":"<p>If you get performance-related pay your employer should base it on clear, measurable targets - they should tell you about these.</p>\n\n<p>There are 2 main types of performance pay:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>short-term schemes, like bonus payments or sales commission</li>\n  <li>long-term schemes, like company shares</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>If you have problems</h2>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t get a bonus or commission you&rsquo;re owed and you think there&rsquo;s been a mistake:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>speak to your employer to see if there&rsquo;s been a misunderstanding</li>\n  <li>ask them set out in writing how they&rsquo;ve calculated your pay</li>\n  <li>keep copies of any letters and notes of any meetings</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If a bonus or commission is included in your contract, non-payment is a breach of contract - read the advice on <a href=\"/solve-workplace-dispute\" title=\"workplace disputes\">workplace disputes</a> if you need help. </p>\n\n<p>Also, non-payment of bonuses may be covered legally under:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>unlawful deductions from wages (eg you&rsquo;re entitled to payment but it hasn&rsquo;t been given)</li>\n  <li>unlawful discrimination (your employer must not discriminate against particular groups, for example giving smaller bonuses to women) </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can also get advice from <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.acas.org.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1461\" title=\"Acas (Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service)\"><abbr title=\"Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service\">Acas</abbr> (Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service),</a> <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/index/getadvice.htm#searchbox\" title=\"Citizens Advice\">Citizens Advice</a> or your trade union representative.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/understanding-your-pay/deductions-from-your-pay","slug":"deductions-from-your-pay","order":5,"title":"Deductions from your pay","body":"<p>Your employer isn&rsquo;t allowed to make deductions unless:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>it&rsquo;s required or allowed by law, eg National Insurance, income tax or student loan repayments</li>\n  <li>you agree in writing </li>\n  <li>your contract says they can</li>\n  <li>there&rsquo;s a statutory payment due to a public authority </li>\n  <li>you haven&rsquo;t worked due to taking part in a strike or industrial action</li>\n  <li>there&rsquo;s been an earlier overpayment of wages or expenses</li>\n  <li>it&rsquo;s a result of a court order</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>A deduction can’t reduce your pay below the <a href=\"/national-minimum-wage-rates\" title=\"National Minimum Wage\">National Minimum Wage</a> rate, even if you’ve agreed to it.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>If you work in retail (eg shops, restaurants)</h3>\n\n<p>Your employer can&rsquo;t take more than 10% from your gross pay (pay before tax and National Insurance) each pay period to cover any shortfalls.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong></p>\n\n<p>There&rsquo;s a shortfall of £50 in your till and your employer wants to deduct this from your earnings. </p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;re paid £250 gross per week. Your employer can take 10% of your gross earnings, which is £25.</p>\n\n<p>They must only take £25 one week and then make another deduction from your next pay cheque for £25.</p>\n\n<p>If you leave your job, they can take the full amount owed from your final pay</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you haven&rsquo;t been paid in full</h2>\n\n<p>Speak to your employer first to try to sort the problem informally. </p>\n\n<p>If this doesn&rsquo;t work, talk to <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.acas.org.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1461\" title=\"Acas (Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service)\"><abbr title=\"Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service\">Acas</abbr> (Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service),</a> <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/index/getadvice.htm#searchbox\" title=\"Citizens Advice\">Citizens Advice</a> or your trade union representative.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You have the right to go to an <a href=\"/employment-tribunals\" title=\"Employment Tribunal\">Employment Tribunal</a> to get your money.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you quit your job</h2>\n\n<p>Check your contract to see if your employer is allowed to withhold your pay. Normally you&rsquo;re entitled to be paid everything you earned up to the point you finished.</p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re forced to resign as a result of your employer refusing to pay you, you might be able to make a constructive dismissal claim in an <a href=\"/employment-tribunals\" title=\"Employment Tribunal\">Employment Tribunal</a>.</p>\n\n"}]},"tags":[{"title":"Your pay, tax and the National Minimum Wage","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working%2Ftax-minimum-wage.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes National Minimum Wage rates, keeping pay records and pay rights","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=working%2Ftax-minimum-wage","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/working/tax-minimum-wage"},"parent":{"title":"Working, jobs and pensions","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes holidays and finding a job","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"conten